  "prompt": "Knighthood: Is it possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible for a non-native British citizen to be knighted. Knighthood is an honor granted by the British monarchy, and it can be awarded to individuals who are not British citizens. However, non-British citizens typically receive honorary knighthoods. These honorary awards allow the recipient to use the honorifics associated with the title, such as \"Sir\" or \"Dame,\" but they do not receive the full privileges of knighted British citizens, such as the right to use \"Sir\" or \"Dame\" before their names in the UK. Notable examples of non-British citizens who have received honorary knighthoods include Bill Gates and Steven Spielberg.",
